<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>A Beginner's Guide to Buddhism</title>
<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Playfair+Display:ital,wght@0,400;0,600;0,700;1,400&family=Nunito:wght@400;500;600;700&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
<style>
  :root {
    --bg: #F7F3ED;
    --card: #FFFFFF;
    --text: #3D3530;
    --text-mid: #6B5E54;
    --text-light: #9A8D82;
    --saffron: #C87A2E;
    --saffron-soft: #E09A4A;
    --saffron-deep: #8E5618;
    --saffron-glow: rgba(200,122,46,0.08);
    --teal: #4A8A7A;
    --teal-soft: #6BAFA0;
    --maroon: #8A4A5A;
    --gold: #B8960B;
    --sand: #D2C4A8;
    --sand-light: #EDE6D8;
    --cream: #FBF8F3;
    --border: #E0D7CB;
    --shadow: rgba(60,45,30,0.06);
    --shadow-md: rgba(60,45,30,0.1);
    --shadow-lg: rgba(60,45,30,0.14);
  }

  * { margin: 0; padding: 0; box-sizing: border-box; }
  html { scroll-behavior: smooth; -webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%; }

  body {
    font-family: 'Nunito', sans-serif;
    background: var(--bg);
    color: var(--text);
    line-height: 1.7;
    min-height: 100vh;
  }

  body::before {
    content: '';
    position: fixed;
    inset: 0;
    background:
      radial-gradient(ellipse at 15% 10%, rgba(200,122,46,0.05) 0%, transparent 50%),
      radial-gradient(ellipse at 85% 90%, rgba(74,138,122,0.04) 0%, transparent 50%);
    pointer-events: none;
  }

  .container {
    max-width: 880px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 2.5rem 1.5rem 4rem;
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
  }

  /* ── Hero ── */
  .hero {
    text-align: center;
    padding: 3rem 2rem 2.5rem;
    background: linear-gradient(160deg, var(--card) 0%, var(--cream) 50%, #F5EFE3 100%);
    border-radius: 20px;
    box-shadow: 0 4px 24px var(--shadow-md);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .hero::before {
    content: '☸';
    position: absolute;
    top: -30px;
    left: 50%;
    transform: translateX(-50%);
    font-size: 6rem;
    color: var(--saffron);
    opacity: 0.07;
  }

  .hero-label {
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.25em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--saffron);
    margin-bottom: 0.6rem;
    display: block;
  }

  .hero h1 {
    font-family: 'Playfair Display', serif;
    font-size: 2.6rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--text);
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    line-height: 1.2;
  }

  .hero h1 span { color: var(--saffron); }

  .hero p {
    color: var(--text-mid);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    max-width: 560px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  /* ── Navigation pills ── */
  .nav-bar {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    gap: 0.45rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
    position: sticky;
    top: 0;
    z-index: 10;
    background: rgba(247,243,237,0.92);
    backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
    padding: 0.8rem 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(224,215,203,0.5);
  }

  .nav-pill {
    font-family: 'Nunito', sans-serif;
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    padding: 0.45rem 1rem;
    border: 2px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 50px;
    background: var(--card);
    color: var(--text-light);
    cursor: pointer;
    transition: all 0.3s ease;
    text-decoration: none;
    box-shadow: 0 1px 4px var(--shadow);
  }

  .nav-pill:hover {
    border-color: var(--saffron-soft);
    color: var(--saffron-deep);
    transform: translateY(-1px);
    box-shadow: 0 3px 10px var(--shadow-md);
  }

  /* ── Section styling ── */
  .section {
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
    scroll-margin-top: 4.5rem;
  }

  .section-header {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.7rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.2rem;
    padding-bottom: 0.7rem;
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--sand);
  }

  .section-num {
    width: 36px;
    height: 36px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--saffron), var(--saffron-soft));
    color: #FFF;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    flex-shrink: 0;
    box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(200,122,46,0.2);
  }

  .section-header h2 {
    font-family: 'Playfair Display', serif;
    font-size: 1.55rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .prose {
    font-size: 0.93rem;
    color: var(--text);
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .prose strong { color: var(--saffron-deep); font-weight: 700; }

  /* ── Cards ── */
  .card-grid {
    display: grid;
    gap: 1rem;
    margin: 1.2rem 0;
  }

  .card-grid-2 { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }
  .card-grid-3 { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr; }
  .card-grid-4 { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }

  .card {
    background: var(--card);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 12px;
    padding: 1.1rem 1.2rem;
    box-shadow: 0 2px 12px var(--shadow);
    transition: transform 0.2s, box-shadow 0.2s;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .card:hover {
    transform: translateY(-2px);
    box-shadow: 0 6px 20px var(--shadow-md);
  }

  .card::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    top: 0;
    left: 0;
    right: 0;
    height: 3px;
    border-radius: 12px 12px 0 0;
  }

  .card-saffron::before { background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--saffron), var(--saffron-soft)); }
  .card-teal::before { background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--teal), var(--teal-soft)); }
  .card-maroon::before { background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--maroon), #B06A7A); }
  .card-gold::before { background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--gold), #D4B62E); }

  .card-label {
    font-size: 0.68rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    margin-bottom: 0.35rem;
  }

  .label-saffron { color: var(--saffron); }
  .label-teal { color: var(--teal); }
  .label-maroon { color: var(--maroon); }
  .label-gold { color: var(--gold); }

  .card h3 {
    font-family: 'Playfair Display', serif;
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--text);
    margin-bottom: 0.35rem;
    line-height: 1.3;
  }

  .card p {
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--text-mid);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  /* ── Eightfold Path wheel ── */
  .path-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 0.7rem;
    margin: 1.2rem 0;
  }

  .path-item {
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start;
    gap: 0.65rem;
    padding: 0.8rem 1rem;
    background: var(--card);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 10px;
    box-shadow: 0 1px 6px var(--shadow);
    transition: transform 0.2s, box-shadow 0.2s;
  }

  .path-item:hover {
    transform: translateY(-1px);
    box-shadow: 0 4px 14px var(--shadow-md);
  }

  .path-dot {
    width: 28px;
    height: 28px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: #FFF;
    flex-shrink: 0;
    margin-top: 0.1rem;
  }

  .dot-wisdom { background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--teal), var(--teal-soft)); }
  .dot-ethics { background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--saffron), var(--saffron-soft)); }
  .dot-mind { background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--maroon), #B06A7A); }

  .path-item strong {
    display: block;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--text);
    margin-bottom: 0.1rem;
  }

  .path-item span {
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: var(--text-light);
    line-height: 1.5;
  }

  /* ── Key terms ── */
  .term-list {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 0.7rem;
    margin: 1rem 0;
  }

  .term {
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    background: var(--cream);
    border-radius: 10px;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--saffron);
  }

  .term dt {
    font-family: 'Playfair Display', serif;
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: var(--saffron-deep);
    margin-bottom: 0.15rem;
  }

  .term dd {
    font-size: 0.82rem;
    color: var(--text-mid);
    line-height: 1.55;
  }

  /* ── Highlight / quote box ── */
  .highlight-box {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--cream), #F5EFE3);
    border: 1px solid var(--sand);
    border-radius: 14px;
    padding: 1.4rem 1.6rem;
    margin: 1.4rem 0;
    text-align: center;
    box-shadow: 0 2px 12px var(--shadow);
  }

  .highlight-box .quote {
    font-family: 'Playfair Display', serif;
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--text);
    line-height: 1.5;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .highlight-box .attr {
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    color: var(--text-light);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* ── Branches table ── */
  .branches {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    margin: 1rem 0;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    border-radius: 12px;
    overflow: hidden;
    box-shadow: 0 2px 12px var(--shadow);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
  }

  .branches thead th {
    background: var(--cream);
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    text-align: left;
    font-family: 'Playfair Display', serif;
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 0.88rem;
    color: var(--saffron-deep);
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--sand);
  }

  .branches tbody td {
    padding: 0.7rem 1rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #EDE8E0;
    vertical-align: top;
    background: var(--card);
  }

  .branches tbody tr:nth-child(even) td { background: #FDFBF7; }
  .branches tbody tr:hover td { background: #F6F0E4; }

  .branches-wrap {
    border-radius: 12px;
    overflow: hidden;
    margin: 1rem 0;
  }

  .branches td:first-child {
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--saffron-deep);
    font-family: 'Playfair Display', serif;
  }

  /* ── Precepts ── */
  .precept-list {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.6rem;
    margin: 1rem 0;
  }

  .precept {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.8rem;
    padding: 0.7rem 1rem;
    background: var(--card);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 10px;
    box-shadow: 0 1px 6px var(--shadow);
    transition: transform 0.2s;
  }

  .precept:hover { transform: translateX(4px); }

  .precept-num {
    width: 30px;
    height: 30px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background: var(--cream);
    border: 2px solid var(--sand);
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--saffron);
    flex-shrink: 0;
  }

  .precept p {
    font-size: 0.88rem;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .precept p strong { color: var(--saffron-deep); }

  /* ── Footer ── */
  footer {
    text-align: center;
    margin-top: 3rem;
    padding: 1.3rem;
    background: var(--card);
    border-radius: 14px;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    box-shadow: 0 2px 12px var(--shadow);
  }

  footer p {
    color: var(--text-light);
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  /* ── Responsive: Tablet ── */
  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .card-grid-3 { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }
  }

  /* ── Responsive: Mobile ── */
  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    .container { padding: 1rem 0.75rem 2.5rem; }

    /* Hero */
    .hero { padding: 1.8rem 1rem 1.5rem; border-radius: 14px; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .hero::before { font-size: 4rem; top: -14px; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 1.65rem; }
    .hero p { font-size: 0.85rem; }
    .hero-label { font-size: 0.65rem; letter-spacing: 0.2em; }

    /* Divider */
    .divider { margin: 1rem 0; }

    /* Nav bar — horizontal scroll on mobile */
    .nav-bar {
      justify-content: flex-start;
      flex-wrap: nowrap;
      overflow-x: auto;
      -webkit-overflow-scrolling: touch;
      padding: 0.6rem 0.75rem;
      gap: 0.4rem;
      scrollbar-width: none;
      -ms-overflow-style: none;
    }
    .nav-bar::-webkit-scrollbar { display: none; }
    .nav-pill {
      font-size: 0.73rem;
      padding: 0.42rem 0.85rem;
      white-space: nowrap;
      flex-shrink: 0;
    }

    /* Sections */
    .section { margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .section-header { gap: 0.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.9rem; padding-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .section-header h2 { font-size: 1.2rem; }
    .section-num { width: 30px; height: 30px; font-size: 0.75rem; }

    /* Prose */
    .prose { font-size: 0.88rem; margin-bottom: 0.8rem; }

    /* Cards — single column */
    .card-grid-2, .card-grid-3, .card-grid-4 { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 0.7rem; }
    .card { padding: 0.9rem 1rem; border-radius: 10px; }
    .card h3 { font-size: 0.95rem; }
    .card p { font-size: 0.82rem; }

    /* Eightfold Path — single column */
    .path-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 0.55rem; }
    .path-item { padding: 0.65rem 0.8rem; gap: 0.5rem; border-radius: 8px; }
    .path-dot { width: 26px; height: 26px; font-size: 0.65rem; }
    .path-item strong { font-size: 0.82rem; }
    .path-item span { font-size: 0.78rem; }

    /* Glossary terms — single column */
    .term-list { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 0.5rem; }
    .term { padding: 0.6rem 0.8rem; }
    .term dt { font-size: 0.85rem; }
    .term dd { font-size: 0.8rem; }

    /* Highlight / quote box */
    .highlight-box { padding: 1.1rem 1rem; border-radius: 12px; margin: 1rem 0; }
    .highlight-box .quote { font-size: 1rem; }
    .highlight-box .attr { font-size: 0.73rem; }

    /* Branches table — horizontal scroll */
    .branches-wrap {
      overflow-x: auto;
      -webkit-overflow-scrolling: touch;
      border-radius: 10px;
      margin: 1rem 0;
    }
    .branches { min-width: 520px; font-size: 0.8rem; }
    .branches thead th { padding: 0.6rem 0.75rem; font-size: 0.82rem; }
    .branches tbody td { padding: 0.55rem 0.75rem; }

    /* Precepts */
    .precept-list { gap: 0.5rem; }
    .precept { padding: 0.6rem 0.8rem; gap: 0.6rem; border-radius: 8px; align-items: flex-start; }
    .precept:hover { transform: none; } /* disable hover shift on touch */
    .precept-num { width: 26px; height: 26px; font-size: 0.7rem; margin-top: 0.1rem; }
    .precept p { font-size: 0.82rem; }

    /* Footer */
    footer { padding: 1rem; border-radius: 12px; margin-top: 2rem; }
    footer p { font-size: 0.75rem; }

    /* Disable hover transforms on touch devices */
    .card:hover { transform: none; }
    .path-item:hover { transform: none; }
  }

  /* ── Very small screens ── */
  @media (max-width: 380px) {
    .hero h1 { font-size: 1.4rem; }
    .hero p { font-size: 0.8rem; }
    .container { padding: 0.75rem 0.55rem 2rem; }
    .section-header h2 { font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .card { padding: 0.75rem 0.85rem; }
    .nav-pill { font-size: 0.68rem; padding: 0.38rem 0.7rem; }
  }
</style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="container">

  <!-- HERO -->
  <div class="hero">
    <span class="hero-label">A Beginner's Guide</span>
    <h1>Understanding <span>Buddhism</span></h1>
    <p>An accessible introduction to the world's fourth-largest faith — its origins, core teachings, practices, and living traditions.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- NAV -->
  <nav class="nav-bar">
    <a class="nav-pill" href="#origins">Origins</a>
    <a class="nav-pill" href="#truths">Four Noble Truths</a>
    <a class="nav-pill" href="#path">Eightfold Path</a>
    <a class="nav-pill" href="#concepts">Key Concepts</a>
    <a class="nav-pill" href="#precepts">Five Precepts</a>
    <a class="nav-pill" href="#branches">Branches</a>
    <a class="nav-pill" href="#practice">Practice</a>
    <a class="nav-pill" href="#glossary">Glossary</a>
  </nav>

  <!-- 1 · ORIGINS -->
  <section class="section" id="origins">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div class="section-num">1</div>
      <h2>Who Was the Buddha?</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="prose"><strong>Siddhartha Gautama</strong> was born around 563 BCE into a royal family in Lumbini (modern-day Nepal). Raised in luxury and shielded from the outside world, he was profoundly affected when — as a young man — he first encountered old age, sickness, death, and a wandering ascetic. These "four sights" led him to renounce his privileged life and seek a deeper understanding of human suffering.</p>
    <p class="prose">After six years of study, asceticism, and meditation, he sat beneath a Bodhi tree in Bodh Gaya (modern Bihar, India) and attained <strong>enlightenment</strong> — a complete and clear understanding of the nature of existence. From that moment he was known as the <strong>Buddha</strong>, which simply means <strong>"the awakened one."</strong></p>
    <p class="prose">He spent the remaining 45 years of his life teaching throughout northern India. He was not a god, prophet, or supernatural being — he was a human being who discovered a path that, he taught, anyone could follow.</p>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <div class="quote">"Do not believe something simply because you have heard it. Test it for yourself."</div>
      <div class="attr">— Adapted from the Kalama Sutta</div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 2 · FOUR NOBLE TRUTHS -->
  <section class="section" id="truths">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div class="section-num">2</div>
      <h2>The Four Noble Truths</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="prose">The Four Noble Truths are the foundation of all Buddhist teaching. Traditionally believed to be the subject of the Buddha's very first sermon, they diagnose the human condition and offer a cure — much like a doctor identifying an illness and prescribing a treatment.</p>

    <div class="card-grid card-grid-2">
      <div class="card card-saffron">
        <div class="card-label label-saffron">First Truth</div>
        <h3>Dukkha — Suffering Exists</h3>
        <p>Life inevitably involves suffering, dissatisfaction, and impermanence. This includes physical pain, emotional distress, and a subtle unease that comes from the fact that nothing lasts. This is not pessimism — it is a realistic starting point.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card card-teal">
        <div class="card-label label-teal">Second Truth</div>
        <h3>Samudaya — The Cause of Suffering</h3>
        <p>Suffering arises from <strong>craving</strong> (tanha) and <strong>attachment</strong> — our constant desire for things to be other than they are. We cling to pleasures, possessions, identities, and outcomes, and this clinging is the root of our dissatisfaction.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card card-maroon">
        <div class="card-label label-maroon">Third Truth</div>
        <h3>Nirodha — Suffering Can End</h3>
        <p>The good news: suffering is not permanent or inevitable. By letting go of craving and attachment, it is possible to reach a state of liberation and deep peace known as <strong>nirvana</strong>.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card card-gold">
        <div class="card-label label-gold">Fourth Truth</div>
        <h3>Magga — The Path to the End of Suffering</h3>
        <p>The practical roadmap to ending suffering is the <strong>Noble Eightfold Path</strong> — a set of eight interconnected practices covering wisdom, ethical conduct, and mental discipline.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 3 · THE EIGHTFOLD PATH -->
  <section class="section" id="path">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div class="section-num">3</div>
      <h2>The Noble Eightfold Path</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="prose">The Eightfold Path is not a sequence of steps to complete one after another — it is eight practices to cultivate <strong>simultaneously</strong>. They fall into three groups: <strong style="color:var(--teal)">Wisdom</strong> (Pañña), <strong style="color:var(--saffron)">Ethical Conduct</strong> (Sīla), and <strong style="color:var(--maroon)">Mental Discipline</strong> (Samādhi). In Pali, "right" (sammā) means "complete, genuine, harmonious" — not a moral judgement.</p>

    <div class="path-grid">
      <div class="path-item">
        <div class="path-dot dot-wisdom">1</div>
        <div><strong>Right Understanding</strong><span>Seeing reality as it truly is — understanding the Four Noble Truths and the nature of impermanence.</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="path-item">
        <div class="path-dot dot-wisdom">2</div>
        <div><strong>Right Intention</strong><span>Cultivating thoughts of renunciation, goodwill, and harmlessness. Committing to ethical and mental self-improvement.</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="path-item">
        <div class="path-dot dot-ethics">3</div>
        <div><strong>Right Speech</strong><span>Speaking truthfully, kindly, and helpfully. Avoiding lies, gossip, harsh language, and idle chatter.</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="path-item">
        <div class="path-dot dot-ethics">4</div>
        <div><strong>Right Action</strong><span>Acting in ways that do not cause harm — not killing, stealing, or engaging in sexual misconduct.</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="path-item">
        <div class="path-dot dot-ethics">5</div>
        <div><strong>Right Livelihood</strong><span>Earning a living in a way that does not cause harm or suffering to others.</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="path-item">
        <div class="path-dot dot-mind">6</div>
        <div><strong>Right Effort</strong><span>Cultivating positive mental states and preventing negative ones. Sustaining energy and enthusiasm for the path.</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="path-item">
        <div class="path-dot dot-mind">7</div>
        <div><strong>Right Mindfulness</strong><span>Maintaining clear, non-judgemental awareness of body, feelings, mind, and mental phenomena moment to moment.</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="path-item">
        <div class="path-dot dot-mind">8</div>
        <div><strong>Right Concentration</strong><span>Developing deep, focused states of meditation (jhāna) that lead to insight and tranquillity.</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 4 · KEY CONCEPTS -->
  <section class="section" id="concepts">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div class="section-num">4</div>
      <h2>Key Concepts</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="prose">Beyond the Four Noble Truths and the Eightfold Path, several core ideas run throughout Buddhist thought. Understanding these helps you make sense of the broader teaching.</p>

    <div class="card-grid card-grid-3">
      <div class="card card-saffron">
        <h3>Karma</h3>
        <p>Literally "action." Every intentional act — by body, speech, or mind — has consequences. Positive actions lead to positive results; harmful actions lead to suffering. Karma is not fate — it is about personal responsibility.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card card-teal">
        <h3>Samsara</h3>
        <p>The ongoing cycle of birth, death, and rebirth that all beings are caught in. Driven by craving and ignorance, beings are reborn again and again across different realms of existence until they achieve liberation.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card card-maroon">
        <h3>Nirvana</h3>
        <p>The ultimate goal — the complete cessation of suffering, craving, and the cycle of rebirth. Nirvana is not a place but a state of profound peace and liberation from all conditioned existence.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card card-gold">
        <h3>Anatta (No-Self)</h3>
        <p>There is no permanent, unchanging "self" or soul. What we think of as "I" is a constantly changing combination of five aggregates: form, sensation, perception, mental formations, and consciousness.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card card-saffron">
        <h3>Anicca (Impermanence)</h3>
        <p>Everything is in a constant state of flux. Nothing — whether physical or mental — remains the same from one moment to the next. Clinging to things as if they were permanent is a major source of suffering.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card card-teal">
        <h3>The Middle Way</h3>
        <p>The Buddha's path avoids both extremes: excessive self-indulgence and severe self-denial. A balanced, moderate approach to life — in practice, diet, and discipline — leads most effectively to wisdom.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 5 · FIVE PRECEPTS -->
  <section class="section" id="precepts">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div class="section-num">5</div>
      <h2>The Five Precepts</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="prose">The Five Precepts are Buddhism's basic ethical guidelines. They are not commandments imposed by a god — they are <strong>voluntary training rules</strong> that Buddhists undertake to reduce harm and develop mindfulness in daily life.</p>

    <div class="precept-list">
      <div class="precept">
        <div class="precept-num">1</div>
        <p><strong>I undertake not to harm or kill living beings.</strong> — Respect for all life; cultivating compassion.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="precept">
        <div class="precept-num">2</div>
        <p><strong>I undertake not to take what is not freely given.</strong> — Honesty and generosity; no stealing.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="precept">
        <div class="precept-num">3</div>
        <p><strong>I undertake to avoid sexual misconduct.</strong> — Responsibility and respect in relationships.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="precept">
        <div class="precept-num">4</div>
        <p><strong>I undertake not to speak falsely.</strong> — Truthfulness; no lying, gossip, or harmful speech.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="precept">
        <div class="precept-num">5</div>
        <p><strong>I undertake to avoid intoxicants that cloud the mind.</strong> — Maintaining clarity and mindfulness.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 6 · BRANCHES -->
  <section class="section" id="branches">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div class="section-num">6</div>
      <h2>The Three Main Branches</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="prose">Over the centuries, Buddhism developed into three major traditions. All share the core teachings of the Buddha, but they differ in emphasis, practice, and the texts they consider most authoritative.</p>

    <div class="branches-wrap">
    <table class="branches">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="width:22%">Branch</th>
          <th style="width:26%">Focus</th>
          <th style="width:26%">Key Texts</th>
          <th style="width:26%">Where Practised</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Theravada</td>
          <td>The original teachings of the Buddha; monastic discipline; individual enlightenment through meditation</td>
          <td>Pali Canon (Tripitaka)</td>
          <td>Sri Lanka, Thailand, Myanmar, Cambodia, Laos</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Mahayana</td>
          <td>Universal compassion; the bodhisattva ideal (delaying one's own nirvana to help all beings)</td>
          <td>Mahayana Sutras (e.g. Lotus Sutra, Heart Sutra)</td>
          <td>China, Japan, Korea, Vietnam, Taiwan</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Vajrayana</td>
          <td>Esoteric rituals, mantra, visualisation; seen as an accelerated path to enlightenment within one lifetime</td>
          <td>Tibetan Kangyur and Tengyur; Tantras</td>
          <td>Tibet, Nepal, Mongolia, Bhutan, parts of Russia</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 7 · PRACTICE -->
  <section class="section" id="practice">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div class="section-num">7</div>
      <h2>Buddhism in Daily Practice</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="prose">Buddhism is not only a set of beliefs — it is a practice. Most Buddhists engage with some combination of the following in their daily lives.</p>

    <div class="card-grid card-grid-2">
      <div class="card card-teal">
        <h3>Meditation</h3>
        <p>The central practice. Two main types are <strong>samatha</strong> (calming the mind through focus, e.g. on the breath) and <strong>vipassana</strong> (insight meditation — observing experience to develop wisdom about impermanence, suffering, and non-self).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card card-saffron">
        <h3>Chanting &amp; Recitation</h3>
        <p>Reciting sutras, mantras, or taking refuge in the Three Jewels (the Buddha, the Dharma, and the Sangha) is common across all traditions and helps focus the mind.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card card-maroon">
        <h3>Ethical Living</h3>
        <p>Following the Five Precepts, practising generosity (dāna), and cultivating compassion and loving-kindness (mettā) in everyday interactions with others.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card card-gold">
        <h3>Community (Sangha)</h3>
        <p>The community of practitioners — both monastic and lay — is one of the Three Jewels. Temples, monasteries, and meditation groups provide support, teaching, and collective practice.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <div class="quote">"The Three Jewels" — the core of Buddhist devotion</div>
      <div class="attr"><strong>Buddha</strong> (the teacher) · <strong>Dharma</strong> (the teaching) · <strong>Sangha</strong> (the community)</div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 8 · GLOSSARY -->
  <section class="section" id="glossary">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div class="section-num">8</div>
      <h2>Essential Glossary</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="prose">Buddhism has its own rich vocabulary, mostly drawn from Pali and Sanskrit. Here are the terms you'll encounter most often.</p>

    <dl class="term-list">
      <div class="term"><dt>Buddha</dt><dd>"Awakened one." Both a title for Siddhartha Gautama and a potential state any being can reach.</dd></div>
      <div class="term"><dt>Dharma / Dhamma</dt><dd>The Buddha's teachings; also translated as "truth," "law," or "the way things are."</dd></div>
      <div class="term"><dt>Sangha</dt><dd>The community of Buddhist practitioners — originally monks and nuns, now often including laypeople.</dd></div>
      <div class="term"><dt>Dukkha</dt><dd>Suffering, dissatisfaction, or unsatisfactoriness — the First Noble Truth.</dd></div>
      <div class="term"><dt>Nirvana / Nibbāna</dt><dd>Liberation from suffering and the cycle of rebirth; the ultimate goal of Buddhist practice.</dd></div>
      <div class="term"><dt>Karma / Kamma</dt><dd>Intentional action and its moral consequences; the law of cause and effect.</dd></div>
      <div class="term"><dt>Samsara</dt><dd>The continuous cycle of birth, death, and rebirth across different realms of existence.</dd></div>
      <div class="term"><dt>Bodhisattva</dt><dd>A being who seeks enlightenment not just for themselves but for all sentient beings (central to Mahayana).</dd></div>
      <div class="term"><dt>Mettā</dt><dd>Loving-kindness; unconditional, universal goodwill toward all beings.</dd></div>
      <div class="term"><dt>Vipassana</dt><dd>Insight meditation — observing reality as it is to develop wisdom about the nature of existence.</dd></div>
      <div class="term"><dt>Sutta / Sutra</dt><dd>A discourse or teaching attributed to the Buddha, recorded in the sacred texts.</dd></div>
      <div class="term"><dt>Deva</dt><dd>A divine or celestial being in Buddhist cosmology — long-lived but not eternal or all-powerful.</dd></div>
    </dl>
  </section>

  <footer>
    <p>This guide is a simplified introduction. Buddhism is a vast and internally diverse tradition spanning 2,500 years of history, philosophy, and practice across many cultures.</p>
  </footer>

